## 4. Architecture Principles

### 4.1 Stage Separation

Each of the four pipeline stages has a single responsibility and a clear boundary. They communicate only through domain records — no stage knows about the internals of another.

```
RuleIntakeService         →  produces  →  Rule (DRAFT, canonical)
CheckpointEvaluationEngine →  produces  →  CheckpointEvaluationReport + RefinementFeedback
LlmRuleRefiner            →  produces  →  Rule (ACTIVE, refined)
PipelineExecutionResponse →  assembles →  all stage outputs for the caller
```

### 4.2 Checkpoints Before LLM

Checkpoint evaluation happens on the **raw standardized rule**, not on the LLM output. This ensures:

- The LLM receives a clear, structured list of quality failures as part of its instructions
- No LLM tokens are wasted refining a rule that hasn’t been quality-assessed first
- Checkpoint failures are auditable independently of what the LLM did with them

### 4.3 Checkpoint as LLM Context

When checkpoints fail, the failures are not discarded — they become the **most important part of the LLM prompt**. The `RefinementFeedbackBuilder` converts each `CheckpointFailure` into a plain-language instruction the model can act on directly.

### 4.4 Pipeline Registry

All pipelines share infrastructure. Adding a new pipeline requires implementing one interface and registering it — no changes to `PipelineExecutor`, `CheckpointEvaluationEngine`, `LlmRouter`, or tracing.

### 4.5 Dependency Hierarchy

```
api  ──►  pipeline / service  ──►  intake / checkpoint / refinement / prompt / llm / response / trace
                                                    │
                                                 domain
                                        (zero framework dependencies)
```

