## 18. Glossary

|Term                          |Definition                                                                                                                  |
|------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
|**Checkpoint**                |A declarative data quality standard defined in JSON. Evaluated against the raw rule **before** LLM refinement.              |
|**CheckpointEvaluationReport**|Full result of evaluating a rule against all applicable scoped checkpoints, including every `CheckpointFailure`.            |
|**CheckpointFailure**         |A single failed checkpoint — carries the failure reason and problematic value, which become LLM instructions.               |
|**CheckpointScope**           |The level a checkpoint applies at: GENERIC (all rules), ENTERPRISE, DOMAIN/LOB, or RULE-specific.                           |
|**CompiledPrompt**            |Fully rendered system + user message pair ready to send to the LLM.                                                         |
|**Pipeline**                  |A named, self-contained LLM workflow. All share checkpoint, prompt, LLM, response, and trace infrastructure.                |
|**PipelineExecutor**          |Routes a `PipelineContext` to the correct `Pipeline` and wraps execution in distributed tracing.                            |
|**PipelineRegistry**          |Central map of `PipelineType → Pipeline` implementations. Populated via Spring component scan.                              |
|**RefinementFeedback**        |Structured payload built from `CheckpointFailure` records and injected into the LLM prompt as fix instructions.             |
|**RuleIntakeService**         |Stage 1 — accepts raw rule, standardizes format, persists as `DRAFT`.                                                       |
|**StructuredResponse**        |Typed, validated wrapper around the LLM’s parsed JSON output.                                                               |
|**Virtual Threads**           |Java 21 Project Loom — high-concurrency I/O without reactive programming, enabled via `spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true`.|

